<subSubSection id="D24C788330E3D32387E915864C381062" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="AD8D345DD6D64923C0C505D9650A8540" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ACDF66E0277BFB9774204AC1CEDD28A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 13 mm (based on 
<taxonomicName id="4041E5498CE3C61FCB580E06D4291472" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">P. cf. normalis</taxonomicName>
), female 11-17 mm. In the concept presented here, 
<taxonomicName id="B4862EFD4744AD937418046DC5D7D2E2" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon normalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="7F048CECD6DA63E765C814D6FC10102F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very variable species in colouration. In females, three colour morphs are recognized. In the typical morph the abdomen and legs are black and the wings are blackish with a subapical yellow marking (
<figureCitation id="734FEC26FF32897F30D9332B7BC00D21" captionStart="Figures 36–47" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 36 - 47. 36 - 46 Wings of Peradon species of the bidens - group: 36 P. bidens ♂ Suriname RMNH 37 P. bispina ♂ holotype 38 P. aurifascia ♂ holotype 39 P. angustiventris ♂ Suriname RMNH 40 P. angustus ♀ neotype 41 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 42 P. normalis var. SUR- 17 B ♀ Suriname RMNH 43 P. normalis typical var. ♀ Suriname RMNH 44 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 45 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 46 P. niger ♂ holotype 47 Wing of P. palpator ♂ holotype (flavofascium group)" figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures36-47" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362280" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures36-47">Figs 43</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="AF83E1E39DECA913CFCACAB1D5CBF4D5" captionStart="Figures 119–128" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figures 119 - 128. Dorsal habitus of Peradon species (bidens group) 119 P.? normalis ♂ Brazil Rondonia LACM 120 P. normalis typical morph ♀ French Guiana RMNH 121 P. normalis red morph ♀ Brazil Para LACM 122 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph ♀ 123 P. niger ♂ holotype 124 P. niger ♀ (holotype M. manni Shannon) 125 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 126 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 127 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 128 P. bispina ♂ Brazil CNC. Scale bar: 10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362292" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128">120</figureCitation>
). In the red morph the abdomen and legs are red, and the wings are coloured as in the typical morph (
<figureCitation id="B9C691DEF298A4ACE16F7DE86F572D46" captionStart="Figures 119–128" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figures 119 - 128. Dorsal habitus of Peradon species (bidens group) 119 P.? normalis ♂ Brazil Rondonia LACM 120 P. normalis typical morph ♀ French Guiana RMNH 121 P. normalis red morph ♀ Brazil Para LACM 122 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph ♀ 123 P. niger ♂ holotype 124 P. niger ♀ (holotype M. manni Shannon) 125 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 126 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 127 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 128 P. bispina ♂ Brazil CNC. Scale bar: 10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362292" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128">Fig. 121</figureCitation>
). In morph SUR-17b the abdomen and legs are black, and the wings are yellow basally with a blackish subapical marking, almost a photo negative of the typical variation (
<figureCitation id="1EFFDE520C269891AE1AC83524CFDDE7" captionStart="Figures 36–47" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 36 - 47. 36 - 46 Wings of Peradon species of the bidens - group: 36 P. bidens ♂ Suriname RMNH 37 P. bispina ♂ holotype 38 P. aurifascia ♂ holotype 39 P. angustiventris ♂ Suriname RMNH 40 P. angustus ♀ neotype 41 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 42 P. normalis var. SUR- 17 B ♀ Suriname RMNH 43 P. normalis typical var. ♀ Suriname RMNH 44 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 45 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 46 P. niger ♂ holotype 47 Wing of P. palpator ♂ holotype (flavofascium group)" figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures36-47" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362280" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures36-47">Figs 42</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="6A7B6A41E27929DC09AA3F0599944512" captionStart="Figures 119–128" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figures 119 - 128. Dorsal habitus of Peradon species (bidens group) 119 P.? normalis ♂ Brazil Rondonia LACM 120 P. normalis typical morph ♀ French Guiana RMNH 121 P. normalis red morph ♀ Brazil Para LACM 122 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph ♀ 123 P. niger ♂ holotype 124 P. niger ♀ (holotype M. manni Shannon) 125 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 126 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 127 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 128 P. bispina ♂ Brazil CNC. Scale bar: 10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362292" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128">122</figureCitation>
). In all of these variations, the alula is largely bare and cell br is largely bare posteriad of the vena spuria. These characters separate 
<taxonomicName id="91DCC6D9F99E1A723B8BCDC9473B440A" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="B8074BC778F4E44DD7125B00CAF53807" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the other species with blackish wings and subapical yellow wing markings: 
<taxonomicName id="B03106D8D1B55D8B0E1A9FDF1F5C1072" genus="P." lsidName="P. bispina" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="bispina">
<emphasis id="E9D2CC92E87B67746AECAC7D6CC7905B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. bispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E3D1248D6555F3C142B19A510F567F1A" genus="P." lsidName="P. niger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis id="507321B4ECBF6A4A89BF2D9223273399" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="612AA74A99A1886A03DE4CAC9258B9EE" genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis id="3B44C399ABA51BDBA8F24682BAA0DB52" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Morph SUR-17b resembles 
<taxonomicName id="B7760F92ED956385A9BB9B7BBB2FFF26" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon flavipennis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis id="1660E41733417345E3898CFE85869FC1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in wing colouration, but differs from that species by the more extensive yellow in the wing and the different position of the dark cloud in the wing, as described in the key. Additional characters distinguishing females of 
<taxonomicName id="B3F1B2C9F0D579B856C465100DB16F64" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="489E8DE6496489787DBE28B65A26EBAE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from females of 
<taxonomicName id="6A1557EAE773A55A09B7F75D552894DB" genus="P." lsidName="P. pompiloides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pompiloides">
<emphasis id="968D650AC823FBF73D9CE8EAEDED094D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pompiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8A6D884C0763D89A18968AFB0D91C823" genus="P." lsidName="P. sciarus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sciarus">P. cf. sciarus</taxonomicName>
are the absence of a basomedian patch of greyish pruinescence on tergite 4 (
<figureCitation id="4F825762C5868A17ADE744F6294CFD44" captionStart="Figures 53–56" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 53 - 56. Tergite 4 of Peradon females 53 P. normalis typical variation (without grey pruinescence), French Guiana RMNH 54 P. normalis red variation (without grey pruinescence), Brazil LACM 55 P. pompiloides paratype (with large basomedian patch of pruinescence) 56 P. cf. sciarus (with large basal area of pruinescence) Peru CSCA." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures53-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362282" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures53-56">Figs 53</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E4CDEEE556F697A3679D55DD46CF71D1" captionStart="Figures 53–56" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 53 - 56. Tergite 4 of Peradon females 53 P. normalis typical variation (without grey pruinescence), French Guiana RMNH 54 P. normalis red variation (without grey pruinescence), Brazil LACM 55 P. pompiloides paratype (with large basomedian patch of pruinescence) 56 P. cf. sciarus (with large basal area of pruinescence) Peru CSCA." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures53-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362282" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures53-56">54</figureCitation>
), and the presence of greyish pruinescence on the basal 1/3 of tergite 3 (
<figureCitation id="E9D3D9488DF72FA4200024AD0313BE28" captionStart="Figures 57–60" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figures 57 - 60. Tergite 2 - 3 of Peradon females in frontodorsal view 57 P. normalis typical morph, French Guiana RMNH 58 P. normalis red morph Brazil LACM 59 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph Suriname RMNH 60 P. pompiloides paratype. Note the similar pattern of grey pruinescence on tergite 3 in all three colour morphs of P. normalis, with pruinescence limited to anterior 1 / 3 of tergite 3. In contrast, the grey pruinescence in P. pompiloides extends over a large part of tergite 3." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60">Figs 57-59</figureCitation>
). These characters are only visible when viewing from a frontal angle. The male is not known with certainty. One male specimen from Brazil (Rondonia) is here preliminarily assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="66A605AD264918664F0EFC9B1A81316B" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">P. cf. normalis</taxonomicName>
because of the partly bare alula and wing cell br, and the presence of small, not interconnected yellow marks in the wing apex (
<figureCitation id="70A2D0643C7B646B396AF850328F69E9" captionStart="Figures 119–128" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figures 119 - 128. Dorsal habitus of Peradon species (bidens group) 119 P.? normalis ♂ Brazil Rondonia LACM 120 P. normalis typical morph ♀ French Guiana RMNH 121 P. normalis red morph ♀ Brazil Para LACM 122 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph ♀ 123 P. niger ♂ holotype 124 P. niger ♀ (holotype M. manni Shannon) 125 P. flavipennis ♀ holotype 126 P. pompiloides ♂ holotype 127 P. pompiloides ♀ paratype 128 P. bispina ♂ Brazil CNC. Scale bar: 10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362292" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures119-128">Fig. 119</figureCitation>
). Genitalia as in 
<figureCitation id="7619B886B34066DA2922ADDCC3CEDBC8" captionStart="Figures 268–273" captionStartId="F46" captionText="Figures 268 - 273. Male genitalia of Peradon species 268 P. costaricensis paratype 269 P.? normalis Brazil Rondonia LACM 270 P. niger holotype 271 P. bispina holotype 272 P. pompiloides holotype 273 P. aurifascia Sao Paulo CNC." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures268-273" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362316" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures268-273">Fig. 269</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="93D0AD5BD8628BCA5F8ECAF1961FBCC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="EE8DA935B1561452F6385ECAAC3201D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F4129E75C57BA2E9FE01F618BBC9B668" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The typical colour morph and the red morph are considered conspecific because of the identical morphology, including the patterns of the wing microtrichosity. The pattern of greyish pruinescence on tergite 3 is also similar in both colour forms (
<figureCitation id="6D394AC56937D32F8F821FAF7570D6B6" captionStart="Figures 57–60" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figures 57 - 60. Tergite 2 - 3 of Peradon females in frontodorsal view 57 P. normalis typical morph, French Guiana RMNH 58 P. normalis red morph Brazil LACM 59 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph Suriname RMNH 60 P. pompiloides paratype. Note the similar pattern of grey pruinescence on tergite 3 in all three colour morphs of P. normalis, with pruinescence limited to anterior 1 / 3 of tergite 3. In contrast, the grey pruinescence in P. pompiloides extends over a large part of tergite 3." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60">Figs 57-59</figureCitation>
). A similar case of colour variation is found in 
<taxonomicName id="C588E8869DF6D1E52169A15614AA51AF" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon bidens" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bidens">
<emphasis id="1E9F62B3275918A4B13E31D27B4BF517" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon bidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the case of 
<taxonomicName id="B84DB45F0097B15C5B3D8138FBEDC47D" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9DA859F4C96E567C901200E062BB65EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17b of 
<bibRefCitation id="C9823BF6CD075C3FC4F666CBA251E5D2" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" author="Reemer, M" journalOrPublisher="Tijdschrift voor Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="27 - 57" refId="B24" refString="Reemer, M, 2014. A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 157: 27 - 57" title="A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" volume="157" year="2014">Reemer (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, the barcode is identical to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4CD7D2C3803055E59A3422EACCE21945" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1A6AECA19FD8179558540A4F8370F81E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17a (see paragraph 
<taxonomicName id="5A72EF62B28B9FEF455EA280A3333B16" genus="Barcode" lsidName="Barcode results" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="results">
<emphasis id="950A97343DDB22FB938C61C585C3AF75" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Barcode results</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="B49397B6E907CF49206FEED351F6ED07" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="548EAF941A1AABABC5F9E4F9D6E551AF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17b does not agree in morphology and colouration with any described species, but 
<taxonomicName id="85785ABD94333546C97F89AC046B1191" genus="P." lsidName="P." pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="838A69AAFD79CA5D74894899865ECB7F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17a corresponds with the type of 
<taxonomicName id="E0B0A6173D9FD0A8D4D35AFE24433174" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="CA134402BFAC5349C67E3E53B1705F88" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in all morphological and colour characters, except that it is smaller (body length 11 instead of 17 mm). The specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="3841D8E6C982B8D17ED770F954E1DB98" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="166F61472A00F1C0C283ADCCE2248244" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17a is identical in morphology and body size to 
<taxonomicName id="4456B322A7D7C84C8B33452A60CAF754" genus="P." lsidName="P." pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D0C029489BC9130F96E31482BC112E9A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17b. Both specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="900AAEF9FEBC7CF89C9C79BD8951C5FC" genus="P." lsidName="P." pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0464B447A90AE88CBC3DEE52AD57B73A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17a and 
<taxonomicName id="F8C547FF14D7612A4C4EBBEA578EFA74" genus="P." lsidName="P." pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7EFF3621F8DD548BCF995C7633EC85F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SUR-17b were collected at exactly the same locality within five minutes on the same day (
<bibRefCitation id="996948DBE4B33344044DCF4D8CCB167B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" author="Reemer, M" journalOrPublisher="Tijdschrift voor Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="27 - 57" refId="B24" refString="Reemer, M, 2014. A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 157: 27 - 57" title="A review of Microdontinae (Diptera: Syrphidae) of Surinam, with a key to the Neotropical genera." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/22119434-00002035" volume="157" year="2014">Reemer 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Combined with the identical barcodes and identical morphology this suggests that the specimens belong to the same species, so both are here assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="26F925D763617D69D3375E48C4EC3070" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="68176838D17186BE6B7277218B69FA6E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Extra support for this conclusion is provided by the similar pattern of greyish pruinescence on tergite 3 (
<figureCitation id="CE4D02CECEE8AB2FE6036FABBA0B967E" captionStart="Figures 57–60" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figures 57 - 60. Tergite 2 - 3 of Peradon females in frontodorsal view 57 P. normalis typical morph, French Guiana RMNH 58 P. normalis red morph Brazil LACM 59 P. normalis SUR- 17 b morph Suriname RMNH 60 P. pompiloides paratype. Note the similar pattern of grey pruinescence on tergite 3 in all three colour morphs of P. normalis, with pruinescence limited to anterior 1 / 3 of tergite 3. In contrast, the grey pruinescence in P. pompiloides extends over a large part of tergite 3." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures57-60">Figs 57-59</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B3CDF3694C5D4B1A35D3C3457B312254" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In the only male specimen assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="95E437D58A59AD666EF5CEAF8EEAC86F" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="0AD46F198D6C56CF726F0870371918D1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the yellow wing markings are not interconnected, so they do not form one large subapical macula as is found in the females of the typical variation. However, such sexual dimorphism in which the yellow wing colouration is less extensive in the male is also known from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="2AB0712222533E5BB922678B807F7223" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D9B25DF8A4E334B1ECFB618CAFABBF5D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="5305145B6BF65203483E6856CEF83156" genus="P." lsidName="P. chrysopygus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chrysopygus">
<emphasis id="5C1108028B2F7D29E95F7058482A0689" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. chrysopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="95DF455F64E9666175667743BA79BBC1" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavofascium" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavofascium">
<emphasis id="5C9786706FC25F8098A0BFB3E59AB8E1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. flavofascium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="061AA5A47C37253BA0E7FECC296065D9" genus="P." lsidName="P. luridescens" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="luridescens">
<emphasis id="8ED86B4C405213BF0469025BBAB80FF5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. luridescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Whether this male specimen really belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="DD8DDCF5DD5D53D95D55A0407C052531" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="CDFA60107022779812CEB8266C7C3CF1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can only be resolved based on additional material, which is currently unavailable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="45534E50D3964EFF49EBD00C3D98A0DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The only known specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="F1CC5CED81E319D86A88612D621DEC2C" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon flavipennis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis id="E24738FFF4A30859433F1999D04ECAD6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only differs from 
<taxonomicName id="185CE01215A23FB1ABC455D1946849DB" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="C1CFA1011DE691B58608824B931B2975" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in wing colouration. Therefore, it seems possible that 
<taxonomicName id="5F61ACB882E9AA7D04094AA44CB31A64" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavipennis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis id="91544A7F806388C4FDC359170EADF477" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is merely a colour form of 
<taxonomicName id="17C7750901BC71F86BCB950D599E72ED" genus="P." lsidName="P. normalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="normalis">
<emphasis id="F2F0AEF597808A382609E2DD7613D824" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. normalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Without any further specimens or DNA data available, however, it seems premature to change the taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName id="24EE60AF0B9142E37D2084019FA4CACD" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavipennis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis id="5FDE4286E89719A891D85A6EED924ACB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17B26BB165C02D8A546A715F101096DD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D92A88C08D53A94E5DD9691221C167F4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B536955B6C2550BA7D71B2DC9A5E3C1D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Known from the Brazilian states 
<normalizedToken id="8BF3F238E19D287B79CB97B1107D4922" originalValue="Pará">Para</normalizedToken>
and Rondonia, French Guiana, Peru, and Suriname.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
